  "prompt": "Why do I look very hot in the mirror, but pretty bad in pictures?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why you might feel you look better in the mirror than in pictures:\n\n1. **Lighting:** The lighting in your room or bathroom may be more flattering than the lighting in the photo. Natural light is often the most flattering, while harsh or artificial lighting can cast unflattering shadows on the face.\n\n2. **Angles:** When you look in the mirror, you typically see yourself from a slightly different angle than when someone takes a photo of you. You might subconsciously position yourself in a way that highlights your best features in the mirror.\n\n3. **Familiarity:** You're used to seeing yourself in a certain way, and your reflection can sometimes feel more \"right\" to you than a photo. Photos can capture a moment that feels less familiar.\n\n4. **Camera Lenses:** Different cameras and lenses can distort features in various ways. For example, wide-angle lenses can exaggerate certain aspects, while close-ups can highlight imperfections.\n\n5. **Self-perception:** In the mirror, you get immediate feedback and can control your expression. In photos, you may be caught off guard, resulting in a pose or expression you're not happy with.\n\n6. **Posture and Confidence:** When you\u2019re looking in the mirror, you may stand differently or project more confidence, affecting how you perceive yourself compared to a candid photo.\n\n7. **Editing and Filters:** If you\u2019ve been using filters or editing tools on social media but not in your mirror reflections, this could also cause a discrepancy in how you see yourself.\n\nIf this is something that bothers you, consider experimenting with lighting, angles, and poses in photos to help find a look that you feel more confident about!",
